title: Sunday's local roundup: Old Dominion field hockey upends No. 5 Virginia 3-2 in 2 OTs
text:
Sunday's local roundup: Old Dominion field hockey upends No. 5 Virginia 3-2 in 2 OTs 
Colleges 
Field hockey: 
Casey Dolan scored six minutes into the second overtime to give No. 15 Old Dominion a 3-2 home win over No. 5 Virginia. 
Bailey Quinn and Teisha King also scored for the Lady Monarchs (8-3).Riley Tata (ex-Norfolk Academy High) and Tara Vittese scored in the second half for the Cavaliers (10-3). Vittese’s goal tied the game with 18:07 left in regulation. 
Women’s volleyball: 
Khaila Donaldson posted 11 kills and nine digs in Howard’s 25-15, 25-20, 25-19 win over Norfolk State. The Bison improved to 8-13, 5-1 in the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference. 
Darcy Moore tallied 24 assists and Alex Irizarry collected 11 digs for the visiting Spartans, who fell to 1-15, 0-3 in MEAC play. 
Women’s soccer: 
Alexis Shaffer scored 13 minutes into the contest to lead No. 3 Virginia to a 1-0 win over Wake Forest in Winston-Salem, N.C. 
It was the third straight win for the Cavaliers (10-1-1, 4-1 ACC), who also have shut out their last three opponents. The Demon Deacons fell to 4-9-2, 1-5 in the ACC. ... 
Clara Logsdon’s goal with 8:27 left in the first half was enough for William and Mary, which beat UNC Wilmington 1-0. 
Nicole Baxter and Haley Kent assisted on the play and Caroline Casey made six saves for the host Tribe (9-3-1, 3-1 CAA). The Seahawks fell to 10-5-1, 3-2-1 in the CAA. ... 
North Texas scored early and added a late insurance goal to come away with a 2-0 win at Old Dominion. 
Karla Pineda scored on a penalty kick less then two minutes into the game and Marchelle Davis scored with 15:31 left in regulation for the Mean Green (12-2-1, 4-0-1 Conference USA). 
The Lady Monarchs fell to 4-9, 2-2 in C-USA. ... 
Dina Isham and Elise Pratt scored two goals each and Tere’ Crawford had two assists in Delaware State’s 11-0 win over Hampton. 
Women’s tennis: 
University of Virginia senior Danielle Collins posted her second championship in a prestigious national tournament, cruising to a straight set victory to claim the Riviera/ITA All-American Championship in Pacific Palisades, Calif. 
Collins defeated Miami’s Sinead Lohan 6-1, 6-2 in the title match. Last month, Collins claimed the championship at the Oracle/ITA Masters tournament in California. 
Collins posted five consecutive straight-set victories on the way to the title. 
U.Va. senior Julia Elbaba also competed on Sunday, playing in the finals of the consolation draw. Elbaba fell to Mississippi State’s Jasmine Lee by a score of 6-1, 6-4.
